'''Kushida Shrine''' (くしだじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Kushida-chō, {{ill|lt=Matsusaka|Q460829|qid=Q460829|1=Matsusaka}}, {{ill|lt=Mie Prefecture|Q128196|qid=Q128196|1=Mie Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}, and under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} its former rank was {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

It is located near the west bank of the lower {{ill|lt=Kushida River|Q6447936|qid=Q6447936|1=Kushida River}}. It is revered by {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=barber|1=UNKNOWN}} and {{ill|lt=beauty|Q2474068|qid=Q2474068|1=Cosmetology}} professionals, and near the precinct stands a “{{ill|lt=comb|Q23834|qid=Q23834|1=Comb}} monument” built by the Mie Prefectural Beauty and Sanitation Trade Association and others. {{ill|lt=Kushida Shrine (Fukuoka)|Q865839|qid=Q865839|lt=Kushida Shrine|1=Kushida Shrine}} in Hakata Ward, Fukuoka City, known for July’s {{ill|lt=Hakata Gion Yamakasa|Q1749262|qid=Q1749262|1=Hakata Gion Yamakasa}} and October’s {{ill|lt=Hakata Okunchi|Q11408922|qid=Q11408922|1=Hakata Okunchi}}, is said to have been founded in {{ill|lt=757|Q31135|qid=Q31135|1=AD 757}} ({{ill|lt=Tenpyō-hōji|Q1346307|qid=Q1346307|1=Tenpyō-hōji}} 1) by inviting this shrine.

=== Enshrined deities ===
Its {{ill|lt=enshrined deities|Q11591100|qid=Q11591100|1=Saijin}} are {{ill|lt=Ōwakago-no-Mikoto|Q111114032|qid=Q111114032|1=Ōwakako no Mikoto}}, Kushitamahime-no-Mikoto, {{ill|lt=Susanoo|Q272993|qid=Q272993|lt=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ame-no-Oshihomimi|1=UNKNOWN}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ichikishima-hime|1=UNKNOWN}}.

Ōwakago-no-Mikoto, according to ''{{ill|lt=Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki|Q131331326|qid=Q131331326|1=Yamatohime no Mikoto Seiki}}'', was a powerful local ruler governing “Takeda no Kuni”; after {{ill|lt=Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|Q4388732|qid=Q4388732|1=Yamatohime-no-mikoto}} interacted with him while visiting this area, a comb fell, so the place was named Kushida and “Kushida-sha” was established<ref>[https://www.matsusaka-kanko.com/information/2017/01/06/櫛田神社/] - “Kushida Shrine,” Matsusaka Tourism Association</ref><ref> ''{{ill|lt=Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki|Q131331326|qid=Q131331326|1=Yamatohime no Mikoto Seiki}}''</ref>.

Also, according to the shrine history, because Ōwakago-no-Mikoto achieved many military merits, Yamatohime-no-Mikoto ordered that he be enshrined as this shrine’s deity.

=== History ===
Shrine tradition says it was founded in year 22 of {{ill|lt=Emperor Suinin|Q314850|qid=Q314850|1=Emperor Suinin}} ({{ill|lt=8 BCE|Q28200|qid=Q28200|1=Ante Christum natum}}), when {{ill|lt=Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|Q4388732|qid=Q4388732|1=Yamatohime-no-mikoto}} was searching for a place to enshrine {{ill|lt=Amaterasu|UNKNOWN|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|qid=Q455602|1=Amaterasu}} and enshrined Ōwakago-no-Mikoto, who guided her here. Around the {{ill|lt=Meireki|Q1192766|qid=Q1192766|1=Meireki}} period in the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|qid=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, shrine buildings were lost and worship lapsed, but it was revived in the {{ill|lt=Kyōhō|Q1145048|qid=Q1145048|1=Kyōhō}} era.

On {{ill|lt=February 27|Q2361|qid=Q2361|1=February 27}}, {{ill|lt=1907|Q2048|qid=Q2048|1=1907}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 40), it was relocated to Aza Murogaito and renamed Ōkushida Shrine with {{ill|lt=merger|Q11412524|qid=Q11412524|1=Co-Enshrinement}}; on {{ill|lt=February 11|Q2335|qid=Q2335|1=February 11}}, {{ill|lt=1908|Q2056|qid=Q2056|1=1908}} (Meiji 41), it was merged into {{ill|lt=Kamiyama Shrine|Q17988632|qid=Q17988632|1=Iinotakamiya-kouyama Shrine}} in Yamazoe-chō. Later, {{ill|lt=ujiko|Q125562175|qid=Q125562175|1=Ujiko}} requested a {{ill|lt=bunshi|Q195793|qid=Q195793|1=Bunrei}}, and on {{ill|lt=February 1|Q2312|qid=Q2312|1=February 1}}, {{ill|lt=1933|Q18726|qid=Q18726|1=1933}} ({{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 8), a divided shrine was re-established at the current site.

On {{ill|lt=September 4|Q2855|qid=Q2855|1=September 4}}, {{ill|lt=2006|Q2021|qid=Q2021|1=2006}} ({{ill|lt=Heisei|Q234510|qid=Q234510|1=Heisei era}} 18) (Comb Day), a “{{ill|lt=comb|Q23834|qid=Q23834|1=Comb}} monument” was erected by the Mie Prefectural Beauty and Sanitation Trade Association and others. The calligraphy was by then {{ill|lt=Minister of Health, Labour and Welfare|Q841962|qid=Q841962|1=Minister of Health, Labour and Welfare}} {{ill|lt=Jirō Kawasaki|Q1689655|qid=Q1689655|1=Jirō Kawasaki}}.

